README.md
     1‚Üí# dotenv
     5‚ÜíDotenv is a zero-dependency module that loads environment variables from a `.env` file into [`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env). Storing configuration in the environment separate from code is based on [The Twelve-Factor App](https://12factor.net/config) methodology.
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí[Watch the tutorial](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtkZR0NFd1g)
     8‚Üí
     9‚Üí&nbsp;
    10‚Üí
    11‚Üí## Usage
    13‚ÜíInstall it.
    14‚Üí
    15‚Üí```sh
    16‚Üínpm install dotenv --save
    17‚Üí```
    18‚Üí
    19‚ÜíCreate a `.env` file in the root of your project:
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí```ini
    22‚Üí# .env
    23‚ÜíS3_BUCKET="YOURS3BUCKET"
    24‚ÜíSECRET_KEY="YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE"
    25‚Üí```
    26‚Üí
    27‚ÜíAnd as early as possible in your application, import and configure dotenv:
    28‚Üí
    29‚Üí```javascript
    30‚Üírequire('dotenv').config() // or import 'dotenv/config' if you're using ES6
    31‚Üí...
    32‚Üíconsole.log(process.env) // remove this after you've confirmed it is working
    33‚Üí```
    34‚Üí
    35‚ÜíThat's it. `process.env` now has the keys and values you defined in your `.env` file:
    36‚Üí
    37‚Üí&nbsp;
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí## Advanced
    43‚ÜíImport with [ES6](#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import):
    44‚Üí
    45‚Üí```javascript
    46‚Üíimport 'dotenv/config'
    47‚Üí```
    48‚Üí
    49‚ÜíES6 import if you need to set config options:
    50‚Üí
    51‚Üí```javascript
    52‚Üíimport dotenv from 'dotenv'
    53‚Üídotenv.config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
    54‚Üí```
    55‚Üí
    56‚Üí</details>
    57‚Üí<details><summary>bun</summary><br>
    58‚Üí
    59‚Üí```sh
    60‚Üíbun add dotenv
    61‚Üí```
    62‚Üí
    63‚Üí</details>
    64‚Üí<details><summary>yarn</summary><br>
    65‚Üí
    66‚Üí```sh
    67‚Üíyarn add dotenv
    68‚Üí```
    69‚Üí
    70‚Üí</details>
    71‚Üí<details><summary>pnpm</summary><br>
    72‚Üí
    73‚Üí```sh
    74‚Üípnpm add dotenv
    75‚Üí```
    76‚Üí
    77‚Üí</details>
    78‚Üí<details><summary>Monorepos</summary><br>
    79‚Üí
    80‚ÜíFor monorepos with a structure like `apps/backend/app.js`, put it the `.env` file in the root of the folder where your `app.js` process runs.
    81‚Üí
    82‚Üí```ini
    83‚Üí# app/backend/.env
    84‚ÜíS3_BUCKET="YOURS3BUCKET"
    85‚ÜíSECRET_KEY="YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE"
    86‚Üí```
    87‚Üí
    88‚Üí</details>
    89‚Üí<details><summary>Multiline Values</summary><br>
    90‚Üí
    91‚ÜíIf you need multiline variables, for example private keys, those are now supported (`>= v15.0.0`) with line breaks:
    92‚Üí
    93‚Üí```ini
    94‚ÜíPRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
    95‚Üí...
    96‚ÜíKh9NV...
    97‚Üí...
    98‚Üí-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----"
    99‚Üí```
   100‚Üí
   101‚ÜíAlternatively, you can double quote strings and use the `\n` character:
   102‚Üí
   103‚Üí```ini
   104‚ÜíPRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\nKh9NV...\n-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\n"
   105‚Üí```
   106‚Üí
   107‚Üí</details>
   108‚Üí<details><summary>Comments</summary><br>
   109‚Üí
   110‚ÜíComments may be added to your file on their own line or inline:
   111‚Üí
   112‚Üí```ini
   113‚Üí# This is a comment
   114‚ÜíSECRET_KEY=YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE # comment
   115‚ÜíSECRET_HASH="something-with-a-#-hash"
   116‚Üí```
   117‚Üí
   118‚ÜíComments begin where a `#` exists, so if your value contains a `#` please wrap it in quotes. This is a breaking change from `>= v15.0.0` and on.
   119‚Üí
   120‚Üí</details>
   121‚Üí<details><summary>Parsing</summary><br>
   122‚Üí
   123‚ÜíThe engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   124‚Üí
   125‚Üí```javascript
   126‚Üíconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   127‚Üíconst buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   128‚Üíconst config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   129‚Üíconsole.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   130‚Üí```
   131‚Üí
   132‚Üí</details>
   133‚Üí<details><summary>Preload</summary><br>
   134‚Üí
   135‚Üí> Note: Consider using [`dotenvx`](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) instead of preloading. I am now doing (and recommending) so.
   136‚Üí>
   137‚Üí> It serves the same purpose (you do not need to require and load dotenv), adds better debugging, and works with ANY language, framework, or platform. ‚Äì [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   138‚Üí
   139‚ÜíYou can use the `--require` (`-r`) [command line option](https://nodejs.org/api/cli.html#-r---require-module) to preload dotenv. By doing this, you do not need to require and load dotenv in your application code.
   140‚Üí
   141‚Üí```bash
   142‚Üí$ node -r dotenv/config your_script.js
   143‚Üí```
   144‚Üí
   145‚ÜíThe configuration options below are supported as command line arguments in the format `dotenv_config_<option>=value`
   146‚Üí
   147‚Üí```bash
   148‚Üí$ node -r dotenv/config your_script.js dotenv_config_path=/custom/path/to/.env dotenv_config_debug=true
   149‚Üí```
   150‚Üí
   151‚ÜíAdditionally, you can use environment variables to set configuration options. Command line arguments will precede these.
   152‚Üí
   153‚Üí```bash
   154‚Üí$ DOTENV_CONFIG_<OPTION>=value node -r dotenv/config your_script.js
   155‚Üí```
   156‚Üí
   157‚Üí```bash
   158‚Üí$ DOTENV_CONFIG_ENCODING=latin1 DOTENV_CONFIG_DEBUG=true node -r dotenv/config your_script.js dotenv_config_path=/custom/path/to/.env
   159‚Üí```
   160‚Üí
   161‚Üí</details>
   162‚Üí<details><summary>Variable Expansion</summary><br>
   163‚Üí
   164‚ÜíUse [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for variable expansion.
   165‚Üí
   166‚ÜíReference and expand variables already on your machine for use in your .env file.
   167‚Üí
   168‚Üí```ini
   169‚Üí# .env
   170‚ÜíUSERNAME="username"
   171‚ÜíDATABASE_URL="postgres://${USERNAME}@localhost/my_database"
   172‚Üí```
   173‚Üí```js
   174‚Üí// index.js
   175‚Üíconsole.log('DATABASE_URL', process.env.DATABASE_URL)
   176‚Üí```
   177‚Üí```sh
   178‚Üí$ dotenvx run --debug -- node index.js
   179‚Üí[dotenvx@0.14.1] injecting env (2) from .env
   180‚ÜíDATABASE_URL postgres://username@localhost/my_database
   181‚Üí```
   182‚Üí
   183‚Üí</details>
   184‚Üí<details><summary>Command Substitution</summary><br>
   185‚Üí
   186‚ÜíUse [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for command substitution.
   187‚Üí
   188‚ÜíAdd the output of a command to one of your variables in your .env file.
   189‚Üí
   190‚Üí```ini
   191‚Üí# .env
   192‚ÜíDATABASE_URL="postgres://$(whoami)@localhost/my_database"
   193‚Üí```
   194‚Üí```js
   195‚Üí// index.js
   196‚Üíconsole.log('DATABASE_URL', process.env.DATABASE_URL)
   197‚Üí```
   198‚Üí```sh
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   319‚Üí## Agents
   323‚Üí> Software is changing, and dotenv must change with it‚Äîthat is why I built [agentic secret storage (AS2)](https://dotenvx.com/as2). Agents run code without humans at terminals, so plaintext `.env` files are the wrong primitive.
   324‚Üí>
   325‚Üí> AS2 is built for autonomous software: encrypted by default, zero console access, and cryptography‚Äëfirst delivery that keeps operators out of the loop.
   326‚Üí>
   327‚Üí> It is backed by [Vestauth](https://github.com/vestauth/vestauth), the trusted, pioneering auth layer for agents‚Äîgiving each agent a cryptographic identity so requests are signed with private keys and verified with public keys. No shared secrets to leak.
   328‚Üí>
   329‚Üí> It's what I'm using now. - [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   330‚Üí
   331‚Üí### Quickstart
   333‚ÜíInstall vestauth and initialize your agent.
   334‚Üí
   335‚Üí```bash
   336‚Üínpm i -g vestauth
   337‚Üí
   338‚Üívestauth agent init
   339‚Üí```
   340‚Üí
   341‚ÜíYour agent `set`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   342‚Üí
   343‚Üí```bash
   344‚Üívestauth agent curl -X POST https://as2.dotenvx.com/set -d '{"KEY":"value"}'
   345‚Üí```
   346‚Üí
   347‚ÜíAnd your agent `get`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   348‚Üí
   349‚Üí```bash
   350‚Üívestauth agent curl "https://as2.dotenvx.com/get?key=KEY"
   351‚Üí```
   352‚Üí
   353‚ÜíThat's it! This new primitive unlocks secrets access for agents without human-in-the-loop, oauth flows, or API keys. It's the future for agents.
   354‚Üí
   355‚Üí&nbsp;
   356‚Üí
   357‚Üí## FAQ
   361‚ÜíNo.
   362‚Üí
   363‚ÜíUnless you encrypt it with [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx). Then we recommend you do.
   364‚Üí
   365‚Üí</details>
   366‚Üí<details><summary>What about variable expansion?</summary><br/>
   367‚Üí
   368‚ÜíUse [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx).
   369‚Üí
   370‚Üí</details>
   371‚Üí<details><summary>Should I have multiple `.env` files?</summary><br/>
   372‚Üí
   373‚ÜíWe recommend creating one `.env` file per environment. Use `.env` for local/development, `.env.production` for production and so on. This still follows the twelve factor principles as each is attributed individually to its own environment. Avoid custom set ups that work in inheritance somehow (`.env.production` inherits values form `.env` for example). It is better to duplicate values if necessary across each `.env.environment` file.
   374‚Üí
   375‚Üí> In a twelve-factor app, env vars are granular controls, each fully orthogonal to other env vars. They are never grouped together as ‚Äúenvironments‚Äù, but instead are independently managed for each deploy. This is a model that scales up smoothly as the app naturally expands into more deploys over its lifetime.
   376‚Üí>
   377‚Üí> ‚Äì [The Twelve-Factor App](http://12factor.net/config)
   378‚Üí
   379‚ÜíAdditionally, we recommend using [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to encrypt and manage these.
   380‚Üí
   381‚Üí</details>
   382‚Üí
   383‚Üí<details><summary>How do I use dotenv with `import`?</summary><br/>
   384‚Üí
   385‚ÜíSimply..
   386‚Üí
   387‚Üí```javascript
   388‚Üí// index.mjs (ESM)
   389‚Üíimport 'dotenv/config' // see https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import
   390‚Üíimport express from 'express'
   391‚Üí```
   392‚Üí
   393‚ÜíA little background..
   394‚Üí
   395‚Üí> When you run a module containing an `import` declaration, the modules it imports are loaded first, then each module body is executed in a depth-first traversal of the dependency graph, avoiding cycles by skipping anything already executed.
   396‚Üí>
   397‚Üí> ‚Äì [ES6 In Depth: Modules](https://hacks.mozilla.org/2015/08/es6-in-depth-modules/)
   398‚Üí
   399‚ÜíWhat does this mean in plain language? It means you would think the following would work but it won't.
   400‚Üí
   401‚Üí`errorReporter.mjs`:
   402‚Üí```js
   403‚Üíclass Client {
   404‚Üí  constructor (apiKey) {
   405‚Üí    console.log('apiKey', apiKey)
   406‚Üí
   407‚Üí    this.apiKey = apiKey
   408‚Üí  }
   409‚Üí}
   410‚Üí
   411‚Üíexport default new Client(process.env.API_KEY)
   412‚Üí```
   413‚Üí`index.mjs`:
   414‚Üí```js
   415‚Üí// Note: this is INCORRECT and will not work
   416‚Üíimport * as dotenv from 'dotenv'
   417‚Üídotenv.config()
   418‚Üí
   419‚Üíimport errorReporter from './errorReporter.mjs' // process.env.API_KEY will be blank!
   420‚Üí```
   421‚Üí
   422‚Üí`process.env.API_KEY` will be blank.
   423‚Üí
   424‚ÜíInstead, `index.mjs` should be written as..
   425‚Üí
   426‚Üí```js
   427‚Üíimport 'dotenv/config'
   428‚Üí
   429‚Üíimport errorReporter from './errorReporter.mjs'
   430‚Üí```
   431‚Üí
   432‚ÜíDoes that make sense? It's a bit unintuitive, but it is how importing of ES6 modules work. Here is a [working example of this pitfall](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-es6-import-pitfall).
   433‚Üí
   434‚ÜíThere are two alternatives to this approach:
   435‚Üí
   436‚Üí1. Preload with dotenvx: `dotenvx run -- node index.js` (_Note: you do not need to `import` dotenv with this approach_)
   437‚Üí2. Create a separate file that will execute `config` first as outlined in [this comment on #133](https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv/issues/133#issuecomment-255298822)
   438‚Üí</details>
   439‚Üí
   440‚Üí<details><summary>Can I customize/write plugins for dotenv?</summary><br/>
   441‚Üí
   442‚ÜíYes! `dotenv.config()` returns an object representing the parsed `.env` file. This gives you everything you need to continue setting values on `process.env`. For example:
   443‚Üí
   444‚Üí```js
   445‚Üíconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   446‚Üíconst variableExpansion = require('dotenv-expand')
   447‚Üíconst myEnv = dotenv.config()
   448‚ÜívariableExpansion(myEnv)
   449‚Üí```
   450‚Üí
   451‚Üí</details>
   452‚Üí<details><summary>What rules does the parsing engine follow?</summary><br/>
   453‚Üí
   454‚ÜíThe parsing engine currently supports the following rules:
   455‚Üí
   456‚Üí- `BASIC=basic` becomes `{BASIC: 'basic'}`
   457‚Üí- empty lines are skipped
   458‚Üí- lines beginning with `#` are treated as comments
   459‚Üí- `#` marks the beginning of a comment (unless when the value is wrapped in quotes)
   460‚Üí- empty values become empty strings (`EMPTY=` becomes `{EMPTY: ''}`)
   461‚Üí- inner quotes are maintained (think JSON) (`JSON={"foo": "bar"}` becomes `{JSON:"{\"foo\": \"bar\"}"`)
   462‚Üí- whitespace is removed from both ends of unquoted values (see more on [`trim`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/Trim)) (`FOO=  some value  ` becomes `{FOO: 'some value'}`)
   463‚Üí- single and double quoted values are escaped (`SINGLE_QUOTE='quoted'` becomes `{SINGLE_QUOTE: "quoted"}`)
   464‚Üí- single and double quoted values maintain whitespace from both ends (`FOO="  some value  "` becomes `{FOO: '  some value  '}`)
   465‚Üí- double quoted values expand new lines (`MULTILINE="new\nline"` becomes
   466‚Üí
   467‚Üí```
   468‚Üí{MULTILINE: 'new
   469‚Üíline'}
   470‚Üí```
   471‚Üí
   472‚Üí- backticks are supported (`` BACKTICK_KEY=`This has 'single' and "double" quotes inside of it.` ``)
   473‚Üí
   474‚Üí</details>
   475‚Üí<details><summary>What about syncing and securing .env files?</summary><br/>
   476‚Üí
   477‚ÜíUse [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to unlock syncing encrypted .env files over git.
   478‚Üí
   479‚Üí</details>
   480‚Üí<details><summary>What if I accidentally commit my `.env` file to code?</summary><br/>
   481‚Üí
   482‚ÜíRemove it, [remove git history](https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/removing-sensitive-data-from-a-repository) and then install the [git pre-commit hook](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx#pre-commit) to prevent this from ever happening again. 
   483‚Üí
   484‚Üí```
   485‚Üínpm i -g @dotenvx/dotenvx
   486‚Üídotenvx precommit --install
   487‚Üí```
   488‚Üí
   489‚Üí</details>
   490‚Üí<details><summary>What happens to environment variables that were already set?</summary><br/>
   491‚Üí
   492‚ÜíBy default, we will never modify any environment variables that have already been set. In particular, if there is a variable in your `.env` file which collides with one that already exists in your environment, then that variable will be skipped.
   493‚Üí
   494‚ÜíIf instead, you want to override `process.env` use the `override` option.
   495‚Üí
   496‚Üí```javascript
   497‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   498‚Üí```
   499‚Üí
   500‚Üí</details>
   501‚Üí<details><summary>How can I prevent committing my `.env` file to a Docker build?</summary><br/>
   502‚Üí
   503‚ÜíUse the [docker prebuild hook](https://dotenvx.com/docs/features/prebuild).
   504‚Üí
   505‚Üí```bash
   506‚Üí# Dockerfile
   507‚Üí...
   508‚ÜíRUN curl -fsS https://dotenvx.sh/ | sh
   509‚Üí...
   510‚ÜíRUN dotenvx prebuild
   511‚ÜíCMD ["dotenvx", "run", "--", "node", "index.js"]
   512‚Üí```
   513‚Üí
   514‚Üí</details>
   515‚Üí<details><summary>How come my environment variables are not showing up for React?</summary><br/>
   516‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   579‚Üí## Docs
   581‚ÜíDotenv exposes four functions:
   582‚Üí
   583‚Üí* `config`
   584‚Üí* `parse`
   585‚Üí* `populate`
   586‚Üí
   587‚Üí### Config
   589‚Üí`config` will read your `.env` file, parse the contents, assign it to
   590‚Üí[`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env),
   591‚Üíand return an Object with a `parsed` key containing the loaded content or an `error` key if it failed.
   592‚Üí
   593‚Üí```js
   594‚Üíconst result = dotenv.config()
   595‚Üí
   596‚Üíif (result.error) {
   597‚Üí  throw result.error
   598‚Üí}
   599‚Üí
   600‚Üíconsole.log(result.parsed)
   601‚Üí```
   602‚Üí
   603‚ÜíYou can additionally, pass options to `config`.
   604‚Üí
   605‚Üí#### Options ‚Ä¶
   607‚Üí##### path
   609‚ÜíDefault: `path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.env')`
   610‚Üí
   611‚ÜíSpecify a custom path if your file containing environment variables is located elsewhere.
   612‚Üí
   613‚Üí```js
   614‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
   615‚Üí```
   616‚Üí
   617‚ÜíBy default, `config` will look for a file called .env in the current working directory.
   618‚Üí
   619‚ÜíPass in multiple files as an array, and they will be parsed in order and combined with `process.env` (or `option.processEnv`, if set). The first value set for a variable will win, unless the `options.override` flag is set, in which case the last value set will win.  If a value already exists in `process.env` and the `options.override` flag is NOT set, no changes will be made to that value. 
   620‚Üí
   621‚Üí```js  
   622‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ path: ['.env.local', '.env'] })
   623‚Üí```
   624‚Üí
   625‚Üí##### quiet
   627‚ÜíDefault: `false`
   628‚Üí
   629‚ÜíSuppress runtime logging message.
   630‚Üí
   631‚Üí```js
   632‚Üí// index.js
   633‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ quiet: false }) // change to true to suppress
   634‚Üíconsole.log(`Hello ${process.env.HELLO}`)
   635‚Üí```
   636‚Üí
   637‚Üí```ini
   638‚Üí# .env
   639‚ÜíHELLO=World
   640‚Üí```
   641‚Üí
   642‚Üí```sh
   643‚Üí$ node index.js
   644‚Üí[dotenv@17.0.0] injecting env (1) from .env
   645‚ÜíHello World
   646‚Üí```
   647‚Üí
   648‚Üí##### encoding
   650‚ÜíDefault: `utf8`
   651‚Üí
   652‚ÜíSpecify the encoding of your file containing environment variables.
   653‚Üí
   654‚Üí```js
   655‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ encoding: 'latin1' })
   656‚Üí```
   657‚Üí
   658‚Üí##### debug
   660‚ÜíDefault: `false`
   661‚Üí
   662‚ÜíTurn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   663‚Üí
   664‚Üí```js
   665‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ debug: process.env.DEBUG })
   666‚Üí```
   667‚Üí
   668‚Üí##### override
   670‚ÜíDefault: `false`
   671‚Üí
   672‚ÜíOverride any environment variables that have already been set on your machine with values from your .env file(s). If multiple files have been provided in `option.path` the override will also be used as each file is combined with the next. Without `override` being set, the first value wins. With `override` set the last value wins. 
   673‚Üí
   674‚Üí```js
   675‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   676‚Üí```
   677‚Üí
   678‚Üí##### processEnv
   680‚ÜíDefault: `process.env`
   681‚Üí
   682‚ÜíSpecify an object to write your environment variables to. Defaults to `process.env` environment variables.
   683‚Üí
   684‚Üí```js
   685‚Üíconst myObject = {}
   686‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ processEnv: myObject })
   687‚Üí
   688‚Üíconsole.log(myObject) // values from .env
   689‚Üíconsole.log(process.env) // this was not changed or written to
   690‚Üí```
   691‚Üí
   692‚Üí### Parse
   694‚ÜíThe engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment
   695‚Üívariables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return
   696‚Üían Object with the parsed keys and values.
   697‚Üí
   698‚Üí```js
   699‚Üíconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   700‚Üíconst buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   701‚Üíconst config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   702‚Üíconsole.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   703‚Üí```
   704‚Üí
   705‚Üí#### Options ‚Ä¶
   707‚Üí##### debug
   709‚ÜíDefault: `false`
   710‚Üí
   711‚ÜíTurn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   712‚Üí
   713‚Üí```js
   714‚Üíconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   715‚Üíconst buf = Buffer.from('hello world')
   716‚Üíconst opt = { debug: true }
   717‚Üíconst config = dotenv.parse(buf, opt)
   718‚Üí// expect a debug message because the buffer is not in KEY=VAL form
   719‚Üí```
   720‚Üí
   721‚Üí### Populate
   723‚ÜíThe engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use. It accepts a target, a source, and options. This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
   724‚Üí
   725‚ÜíFor example, customizing the source:
   726‚Üí
   727‚Üí```js
   728‚Üíconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   729‚Üíconst parsed = { HELLO: 'world' }
   730‚Üí
   731‚Üídotenv.populate(process.env, parsed)
   732‚Üí
   733‚Üíconsole.log(process.env.HELLO) // world
   734‚Üí```
   735‚Üí
   736‚ÜíFor example, customizing the source AND target:
   737‚Üí
   738‚Üí```js
   739‚Üíconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   740‚Üíconst parsed = { HELLO: 'universe' }
   741‚Üíconst target = { HELLO: 'world' } // empty object
   742‚Üí
   743‚Üídotenv.populate(target, parsed, { override: true, debug: true })
   744‚Üí
   745‚Üíconsole.log(target) // { HELLO: 'universe' }
   746‚Üí```
   747‚Üí
   748‚Üí#### options ‚Ä¶
   750‚Üí##### Debug
   752‚ÜíDefault: `false`
   753‚Üí
   754‚ÜíTurn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being populated as you expect.
   755‚Üí
   756‚Üí##### override
   758‚ÜíDefault: `false`
   759‚Üí
   760‚ÜíOverride any environment variables that have already been set.
   761‚Üí
   762‚Üí&nbsp;
   763‚Üí
   764‚Üí## CHANGELOG
   766‚ÜíSee [CHANGELOG.md](CHANGELOG.md)
   767‚Üí
   768‚Üí&nbsp;
   769‚Üí
   770‚Üí## Who's using dotenv?
   772‚Üí[These npm modules depend on it.](https://www.npmjs.com/browse/depended/dotenv)
   773‚Üí
   774‚ÜíProjects that expand it often use the [keyword "dotenv" on npm](https://www.npmjs.com/search?q=keywords:dotenv).
